\f2\fs20 \cf0 As Sam Ventura packed his bags and headed to New York City in the summer of 2009, he thought he had it all planned out.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The Woodland Hills graduate was breezing through a computational finance degree at Carnegie Mellon University and had landed a prestigious internship on Wall Street. The opportunity was intended to open a door and offer a glimpse into Ventura's lucrative future in finance.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Well, that summer was formative ... just not how Ventura imagined. Turns out, he hated it.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 So now what? Ventura thought back to his childhood in Swissvale, where he'd round up neighborhood kids for a game of street hockey on the tennis court or scour through box scores in the morning paper. He began to shift his focus with the help of Andrew Thomas, a CMU professor and accomplished researcher in the sports analytics field.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Now, 10 years and three CMU degrees later, Ventura, 32, has found his calling. Instead of Wall Street, Ventura makes his living at 1001 Fifth Ave. as an analyst for the Penguins.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Since joining the club as a consultant in 2015 and later a full-time employee, Ventura's voice within the organization has grown and evolved. This upcoming season, the Penguins might get to tap into Ventura's expertise more than ever.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Ventura added to his job description this offseason when Jim Rutherford named him director of hockey operations and research. The promotion coincides with the NHL preparing to introduce puck and player tracking, a new frontier that will give data scientists and analytics experts more information than ever.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 To understand why the Penguins added to Ventura's list of responsibilities and what the tracking data means, it's important first to understand how we got here.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 PAPER, PROFESSOR, CALL
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The timing was nearly perfect for Ventura. Just as he began diving into the world of sports analytics, hockey was in the midst of a data revolution.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 As recently as the 1990s, players couldn't even get their hands on some of the most basic stats like hits, blocked shots or time on ice to make their cases at arbitration. But when the NHL began to release real-time scoring stats publicly in the mid-2000s, a grassroots group of bloggers and analysts emerged. They used that data to create new stats and analysis, including popular shot-based metrics like Corsi.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 At the same time, Thomas had his students at CMU read a number of sports analytics papers and then discuss what they would do differently. When Ventura read about how Brian Macdonald extended basketball's adjusted plus-minus framework into hockey, he proposed an idea of how to tweak it.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 What was supposed to be nothing more than a classroom exercise soon became a spark that would ignite Ventura's sports analytics career. That discussion evolved into an academic paper by Thomas and Ventura titled "Competing Process Hazard Function Models for Player Ratings in Ice Hockey."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The sports analytics community took notice. As Ventura completed a master's degree and later a PhD, he and Thomas began presenting their work at conferences.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Then came a pivotal moment in 2014. The leading source for publicly available hockey data, ExtraSkater.com, was folding. The reason was somewhat bittersweet.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The Toronto Maple Leafs and then-28-year-old general manager Kyle Dubas had hired Extra Skater's creator, Darryl Metcalf. It was one of the first times the NHL offered a seat at the table to a member of the hockey analytics community.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 While it was a huge win for people who had spent years pouring over spreadsheets and charts, Extra Skater's disappearance created a void. Ventura and Thomas seized the opportunity. Within a weekend, they were hammering out code and creating the framework for what would eventually become War-on-Ice.com, a website that arguably became the most significant hockey analytics site of its time.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "We had done all this work, but nobody really noticed it because it was all in academic journals," Ventura said. "We created the website, sort of as a way to get the word out there a little bit better."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 As War-on-Ice.com grew, so too did the NHL's interest in analytics. Metcalf's hiring soon opened the pipeline for many more highly educated outsiders. The Capitals hired Tim Barnes, the man often credited for naming Corsi. The Oilers hired blogger Tyler Dellow. The Devils hired Sunny Mehta, a former pro poker player. Today, virtually all 32 teams employ some type of data scientist or analytics guru.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The Penguins didn't take long to join the analytics revolution. In 2015, former assistant general manager Jason Karmanos called Ventura and offered him an opportunity to join his hometown team as a consultant. Meanwhile, Thomas joined the Minnesota Wild as the lead researcher. Quickly, Ventura earned a full-time position and began climbing the ranks within the front office.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "It wasn't something that was really in the forefront of my mind as something I wanted to do in the short run," Ventura said. "The biggest surprise is how quickly things progressed from War on Ice to where I am now. It's been an exciting six years now."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 A NEW FRONTIER
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Considering how significant Thomas was in Ventura's development, maybe it's fitting that the next step comes with an assist from his former CMU professor.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 In March, Thomas was named director of 
\f0\i\b \ul data science
\f2\i0\b0 \ulnone  at SportsMEDIA Technology, the company that the NHL has contracted to build its player and puck tracking.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Thomas is tasked with leading the analysis and interpretation of this new tracking data.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 To the general fan, the data will likely be presented during game broadcasts in oversimplified snapshots. How fast was that shot? How long did a team get pinned in their defensive zone? How quickly did that skater speed down the ice on that breakaway?
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Those things are kind of cool and easily digestible, sure, but not incredibly illuminating for analysts. And the NHL isn't expected to release all the data to the public, so popular analytics websites and accounts don't expect it to significantly reshape their stats and metrics.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 However, behind the curtain, each NHL team will get what SMT is calling a "firehose of data." Players will produce 200 data points a second and the puck will register 2,000 data points a second. More than the sheer quantity of data, it's the type of information that's exciting for Ventura.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "The data that's currently available publicly really focuses on specific events that happen on the ice," Ventura said. "A shot. A hit. A faceoff. Things like that.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "This data is fundamentally different. Instead of just looking at specific events, it's giving you the locations and the trajectories of all players on the ice and the puck, at every moment in time. It lets you look at things that you would never even be able to begin to explore with data otherwise, things like positioning of defensemen and goalies, how much space is being created by particular players."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 By accessing player locations, NHL analysts who can get their hands on this information will be able to refine and create some new metrics.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 For example, by registering where each player is on the ice for a shot or pass, advanced stats like "expected goals" might be improved. Passing stats, which are not currently tracked by the NHL, will be calculated in new and different ways.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 By measuring distance between players, the concept of gap control could be analyzed like never before. The impact of a net-front screen can be quantified, and blocked shots can be studied to add some science to some of the most fundamental elements of the game.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "People are good at saying, this player is this good," Ventura said. "But they're not quite so good at saying why.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "Why are players having success; why are players struggling? Why are teams having success; why are teams struggling? I think that's the area where the biggest changes are going to come in the short-term future."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 At least initially, storing and trying to figure out what all this data means will be a challenge in and of itself.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 But with virtually all 32 teams employing some type of data scientist or analyst, the race is officially on to try to organize and interpret this new information with the hopes of finding even the smallest competitive advantage.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "It's an exciting time," Ventura said. "When you look at what's happened in other sports, there's been an explosion of information available to fans and to teams. Hopefully, that happens in hockey, as well."
\f3\fs24 \
