\f2\fs20 \cf0 With new data from Carnegie Mellon University, there's now a way to see how many of your neighbors say they mask up.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 CMU's Delphi Research Group has expanded its COVIDcast project, the university's platform to collect, analyze and provide localized information about the novel coronavirus. Since April, researchers have been gathering data about COVID-19 through hospital and medical records and surveys.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The data - which can be broken down by state, metro area or county - look at things like how many people search for COVID-19 on Google, how many COVID-related doctors' visits are scheduled and how often people leave their home and for how long.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The project is meant to help forecast the spread of COVID-19, or predict when and where case numbers could spike. COVIDcast began forecasting the spread of the virus in June and sharing those predictions with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in July.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Now, it has expanded its survey to include questions about access to testing and how people are responding to public health recommendations, like wearing a mask in public.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Based on the self-reported data, most respondents in Allegheny County and surrounding areas have been opting to mask up.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 In the first days of October, the data showed about 93% of respondents in Allegheny said they wear a mask most or all of the time while in public.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 In Washington, Westmoreland, Erie and Beaver counties, between 84% and 87% of respondents said they wore a mask.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Several surrounding counties, like Greene, Forest, Venango and Somerset, did not have any data available.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The CDC recommends individuals wear a mask when in public or when around others who do not live in their household to prevent the spread of the virus. In Pennsylvania, state officials mandated masks for employees and customers in businesses in April and then for anyone leaving their home in July.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 At CMU, the researchers added the question as another way to help predict the spread of COVID-19 and determine what measures are successful in preventing a rise in infections.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The data is not meant to replace official public health reporting on COVID-19, but researchers hope it will supplement decisions made about new health and safety guidelines.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "By providing these signals to the public, we hope to give researchers, public health officials and journalists the information they need to form a more complete picture of the pandemic," Alex Reinhart, an assistant teaching professor in CMU's Department of Statistics and 
\f0\i\b \ul Data Science
\f2\i0\b0 \ulnone  and a member of the Delphi group, said in a prepared statement.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 In Pennsylvania, 87% of respondents said they wore a mask most or all of the time. Comparatively, in Wyoming, only 61% of respondents said they wore a mask, the lowest percentage of any state based on the available data Monday.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 More than 1 million U.S. residents have responded to the expanded survey since it rolled out last month, according to a press release.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 CMU has partnered with Google, Facebook and the University of Maryland on COVIDcast. Facebook distributes the survey to users each day but does not see the results, researchers say. CMU also does not see the identity of the survey respondent.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Google donated $1 million and 12 pro bono fellows to the initiative in September.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 CMU's Delphi group is used to this type of work. It has been forecasting influenza for the past several years and was recently named one of two National Centers for Excellence for Influenza Forecasting by the CDC.
\f3\fs24 \
