\f2\fs20 \cf0 A Carnegie Mellon University student has sued the school in federal court and is seeking a refund for tuition and fees for the spring semester, saying CMU's online instruction isn't an adequate substitute for the real thing.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The suit, brought by undergraduate student Abigale Pfingsten, is seeking class-action status on behalf of all students like her affected by the shutdown of the campus in response to the coronavirus pandemic.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The breach-of-contract suit is similar to one filed earlier this month in federal court by two students against the University of Pittsburgh and mirrors others brought against universities around the country.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "The online learning options being offered to CMU students are subpar in practically every aspect and a shadow of what they once were, from the lack of facilities, materials, and access to faculty," the suit says. "Students have been deprived of the opportunity for collaborative learning and in-person dialogue, feedback, and critique."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Ms. Pfingsten is studying statistics and 
\f0\i\b \ul data science
\f2\i0\b0 \ulnone  as well as international relations, all of which rely on in-person instruction, peer collaboration and access to CMU facilities. She said she's also taking an acting class which similarly relies on in-person contact.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The suit says she and other students who have paid tuition and fees for the spring semester lost the benefit of the education for which they paid and want their money back.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 CMU hasn't held any in-person classes since March 6 but hasn't refunded any payments.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The suit is asking for a return of the pro-rated portion of the tuition and fees for the time that remained in the spring semester when classes moved online.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The school on Tuesday released the following statement:
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "While Carnegie Mellon does not comment on specifics of pending litigation, this unprecedented spring semester was defined by the dedication and flexibility of the entire CMU community," it reads. "Our faculty and staff seamlessly transitioned more than 2,400 classes to remote instruction in just a few days, allowing the university to fulfill our educational mission by delivering excellent instruction remotely to allow students to complete the academic year after the governor's order suspended in-person instruction. These efforts, combined with the determination of our students, were highlighted this past weekend when the university proudly celebrated the success of our graduates and the conferral of 5,436 degrees."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 CMU also said that the university did provide pro-rated housing and dining fees back to students who did not return to campus.
