\f2\fs20 \cf0 Melaney Chen spends most of her day designing 3D models of camera parts that help Uber's autonomous vehicles see objects on the road. She then sends the specs downstairs to the machine shop, where they're built and tested.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "I'll design something today and have a prototype tomorrow or the next day after that," said Ms. Chen, a rising senior at Cornell University who is completing a mechanical engineering internship on Uber's hardware team.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 With its sleek open-concept space and complimentary coffee bar at the Strip District-based engineering office, startups like Uber can conjure up romanticized images of the Silicon Valley scene.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Realistically, though, "startup culture" is not as homogeneous as you'd imagine and work experiences can vary wildly - even for summer interns. A student at a resource-strapped, early stage startup will have a very different summer from an intern at a company on the verge of going public.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 And competition for interns among companies is fierce.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Ride-hailing giant Uber, which is flush with cash, has the ability to hire nearly seven dozen student workers across the country, while smaller, lesser-known companies may not have the bandwidth or reputation to support even one.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "For tech startup hiring, a lot of it depends on funding or what contracts they get," said Kevin Collins, a senior assistant director at Carnegie Mellon University's Career and Professional Development Center. Startup size matters
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Although Uber hardly mirrors a startup anymore - the company employs 1,500 across its San Francisco, Toronto and Pittsburgh engineering offices and is valued at $62 billion -the location on 33rd Street still feels like one.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 That's because it's home to the Advanced Technologies Group responsible for self-driving tech. The office has more of a research and development focus and less bureaucratic structure.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 By virtue of Uber's growth, there are several measures in place that feel like a traditional company, like intern onboarding. Student workers are introduced to the company in the same weeklong module as permanent employees.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 At TravelWits, an Oakland-based startup that aggregates the cheapest combinations of flights and car travel, intern onboarding is far different because there isn't a human resources staff dedicated to internships.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Although the company has only six employees, it has managed to hire and train 10 interns over its four-year history, largely by developing a clever way to improve training with the help of past interns.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "With every intern that comes in, we'll have some sort of documentation, and, as the interns go through the process, they'll add to that documentation," co-founder Arman Bimatov said. Competing for interns
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 This year, Uber received more than 3,000 applications for 80 intern spots. That translates to a roughly 2 percent acceptance rate, placing Uber as one of the most selective internships in the country.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The interview process, which consists of multiple rounds of behavioral and technical challenges, is similar to how most tech firms recruit. Depending on the role sought, Uber's process consists of a mix of live coding challenges, virtual presentations and problem-solving projects.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 While interns compete for spots at companies like Uber, for smaller startups, the inverse is true: They must fight for interns.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 BlastPoint - which helps businesses harness the power of big data and maps - has to compete for talent with household names such as Google and Amazon. The East Liberty-based company, founded in 2016, has raised about $150,000 in a few seed rounds and now has eight employees.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Co-founder Alison Alvarez's strategy is to hire from what she terms "overlooked populations." She finds employees from coding bootcamps or even self-taught engineers rather than through the university recruitment system.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "I'm sure there are a lot of companies in the Pittsburgh area that are struggling to hire data scientists. I'm just looking in a different place than a lot of those companies are," she said. From intern to job offer
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 As the tech industry has grown tremendously - this year, five tech firms delivered half of Standard & Poor's 500-stock index gains - so has demand for tech talent.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Employers at both large and small startups agree that an effective way to secure a "pipeline of talent" is to provide internship programs that lead to full-time jobs, according to Mr. Collins.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "A key reason we offer the internship program is for people to get their foot in the door and give them an idea of what it's like to actually work here," said Michaela Kron, public relations manager for Duolingo, an East Liberty-based language learning app that has a $700 million valuation.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The hiring rationale is a little different for smaller early-stage startups that may not have the scale for full-fledged internship programs.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "They're not as good as Google, for instance, at predicting their hiring needs nine months in advance," Mr. Collins said. "[Those] might change year to year, they might only need software engineers one year versus marketing students the next." Possible complications
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Last summer, John Curcio, a rising junior statistics major at CMU, joined BlastPoint as a 
\f0\i\b \ul data science
\f2\i0\b0 \ulnone  intern.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "John's name is actually on one of our patent applications, we had him doing real research," Ms. Alvarez said.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 At small startup companies, intern contributions - and their level of access to company data - are not immaterial. They often make major contributions to code, develop product features or even design company logos. Firms must walk a fine line to ensure sensitive information is protected and that they're not overworking an intern.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Seth Oranburg, assistant professor of law and innovation at Duquesne University, said it's standard practice for tech companies to require that employees sign a Proprietary Information and Inventions Agreement, along with sending their offer letter.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Signing it basically guarantees that any intellectual property produced by the employee belongs to the company.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "For unpaid internships, the educational benefits to the intern need to outweigh what the intern is giving up, in the case of startups, the intellectual property they're contributing to," Mr. Oranburg said.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 If a company is sued over an unpaid internship, and the court rules in favor of the intern, all intellectual property agreements are nullified.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 At Uber, interns are paid a competitive salary and sign the same nondisclosure agreement that employees do, because all of them will either work on projects with or are exposed to sensitive company information.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "I've always wanted to work in the transportation industry, and this is one of the most cutting-edge realms of it," said Ms. Chen at Uber. "Being here, you really do begin to see the possibility of having self-driving cars . knowing that it's possible and seeing how it's actually done is really inspiring."
