\f2\fs20 \cf0 Mary Johnston has found a new weapon in her ongoing battle to limit her family's cell phone use.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Scare tactics. And she's not talking her frightening monthly bill.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The universal popularity of the cell phone took a hit last week when the head of the prestigious University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute warned that it could have health risks, especially to younger users.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The safety issue is far from a consensus among researchers, but the respected Dr. Ronald Herberman said in a memo to 3,000 faculty and staff that a "growing body of literature" suggests that cell phones have "possible adverse health effects, including cancer."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The memo caused a media frenzy, was reported on by all major news outlets and was a call-in segment on "Larry King Live" last week. Dr. Herberman now plans to conduct a research project on the subject.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 For Ms. Johnston, of White Oak, the warning is "a godsend."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "The truth is," the mother of three teenagers said, "we don't know how cell phones will affect us down the line. They are a relatively new phenomenon. I've lost the battles on phone safety -- some of my family actually drives while talking -- to say nothing of the cost of [a plan for three teenagers and a husband who travels].
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "With this report, I got their attention now -- at least for a while," Ms. Johnston said.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Among Dr. Herberman's recommendations to minimize risks: Reduce length of conversations; use speaker phones, headsets or hand-held devices instead of holding phone to the ear; keep phone battery away from your body; keep children away, except for emergency calls. He also recommended that younger people text, rather than call.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 But Mrs. Johnston thinks the latter is "only a marginally safer idea.''
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "I've seen people text while they drive,'' she said.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 We Asked, You Said
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Whether the cell phone report is one that merits a family roundtable remains to be seen. Still, when we asked, we found that some residents of the South Hills are erring on the side of caution. Others want more info before making an important lifestyle change.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "This just confirms for me the concerns I already had [about] brain cancer,'' said Robert Matzen, of Bethel Park.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "Now I am really careful to keep my conversations short,'' said Mr. Matzen, 46, an independent filmmaker for Paladin Communications, of Bethel Park.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Similarly, Dena Zaimes, 60, of Upper St Clair, said that now she and her husband are "definitely interested in buying a hands-free device for our car."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Already, she said, the couple tries to "shorten conversations and we are more aware of where the phone is placed."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Mrs. Zaimes is the owner of Elegant Accent Catering in Upper St. Clair.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Vicki Yehnert, of Bethel Park, said she is considering the use of more technology.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "I just learned of a device that claims to negate the effects. It's a little disc that you put in your cell phone to eliminate the electromagnetic fields. So my plan is to purchase it,'' said Mrs. Yehnert, 55, a homemaker.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The report, said Rachelle Pasquini, of Baldwin Borough, "created a big conversation in our house."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Ms. Pasquini, 44, who works at Allegheny Children's Initiative on the South Side, said she now "refuses to let my kids get a cell phone until they are at least 16."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Also paying heed is Joanne McKown, of Whitehall.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "Now I carry my cell phone with the battery away from me,'' said Ms. McKown, 51, manager at Curves in Brentwood Town Square.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Hands-Free Phones
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Many are going to Bluetooth, or hands-free wireless technology.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "I work [in academic affairs] at Pitt, and I'm paying attention to the report. Now I plan to get Bluetooth and told my kids to text, not call,'' said Carol Tatrai, 49, of West Homestead.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Stephanie Dickson, of Homestead, sees it another way.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "I don't like Bluetooth, it scares me, people talking to themselves. I do text message. Does that mean I'll get finger cancer?'' asked the 25-year-old waitress at Mitchell's Fish Market at The Waterfront.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Health scare or not, many we talked to said they will not alter what has become a way of life. It's estimated that about 3 billion cell phones are used each day.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Michael Folino, of Beechview, is among the users.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "There's not enough 
\f0\i\b \ul data. Science
\f2\i0\b0 \ulnone  always flip-flops on what is good for you or bad for you. One day eggs are good and the next day they're bad. Wine is bad and then wine is good,'' said Mr. Folino, 29, who owns Folino Brothers Pizzeria in Scott.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Daniel Burns, a Duquesne policeman, also is not limiting his use.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "These days, someone finds something wrong with anything new. I've not seen any definitive medical evidence, so I won't limit use," said Mr. Burns, 45, of Duquesne.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "In my business, I travel and need to be in touch all the time,'' said Douglas Wesolek, 28, of Dormont, who owns West Liberty Detailing in that town.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "I can't give up this convenience. Remember, we're all going to die someday.''
