\f2\fs20 \cf0 It used to be easy to figure out what companies did. U.S. Steel made steel. Heinz made ketchup. Mellon took your money.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Nowadays, it's more difficult. U.S. Steel became USX and bought an oil company. Heinz makes frozen dinners and dog food. Mellon still takes your money, but sometimes it calls itself Dreyfus.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The advent of the Computer Era has greatly complicated things. Now there are companies with unpronounceable names that do inexplicable things. Our text this week is the 1997 directory of the Pittsburgh High Technology Council.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Granted, most company names are notoriously meaningless - have you ever stopped to think what exactly ''Microsoft'' means? - but high-tech companies tend to outdo each other in this regard. One of the fiercest battlegrounds can be found under the letter D, as in ''data.''
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The directory lists Data Resource Management, 
\f0\i\b \ul Data Science
\f2\i0\b0 \ulnone  Automation, Data Task, DataMatrix Systems, Datasoft USA, DataTrain Institute and DataTran. Many more have data somewhere else in their names, but I didn't have all day.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Several forces are at work here. Foremost is the very use of the word ''data.'' Do you think people would take seriously a company called Information Task? Or one called FactTran? It sounds like one of those healthy breakfast cereals. (Oops. Sorry. I must have been thinking of FactBran.)
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Another key strategy is the clever use of capital letters in the middle of words. This immediately signifies your company as futuristic and forward-looking.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Think about it: Would you buy a used car from a place called Joe's Junk Yard? Probably not. What if it were called JoesJunk? Gee, you'd say, this Joe seems like a hip kinda guy. Maybe I'll take a look. Rename it JoesDataJunk and Joe's sales reach a million dollars in six months.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Perhaps your company has an honored family name and sells old-fashioned products, like ''Uncle Fred's Typewriter Repair.'' Don't despair. Just add a ''.com'' to the end of your name and advertise a Web site, even if you don't have one. It's the name that counts.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Of course, no amount of clever nomenclature can hide the fact that almost nobody - including, probably, some of the people who work there - can figure out what these companies actually do.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Open the 1997 high-tech book at random. Here is a company that ''is dedicated to providing communications solutions for clients through the use of paper and electronic-based products.'' Paper? Are they serious? They must have thought this was the low-tech council.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Worse, the company's solutions aren't even innovative. Doesn't it understand that people want innovative solutions, or at least integrated ones? Plain old ''communications solutions'' don't cut it anymore.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Here is a company that ''integrates leading-edge technologies to solve business-critical problems in key market segments.''
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Clearly, this is a company that knows what it's doing. I count at least four buzzwords in that description, and I'm not even an expert. I have no idea what they do. They're hired.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Here is a company that ''designs and manufactures modular adsorption equipment for liquid and vapor-phase purification in process and environmental applications.''
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Hmm. I think I'll just call a plumber.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Here is a company that ''develops and markets application development products and services for building large-scale, mission-critical applications that are graphical, distributed, and cross-platform.''
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 At the risk of exposing my ignorance, I must confess that I am totally lost. Maybe it's not all my fault. This description could use a little zip. How about this:
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 ''Our company develops innovative and integrated solutions for large-, small- and medium-scale buildings - any of which Superman could leap in a single bound! We also distribute 'Mission: Impossible' (starring Tom Cruise) applications that contain some graphic violence on train platforms. Viewer discretion is advised.''
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 There. Doesn't that sound better? I don't know about you, but I'm going out to get mine right away. Just one question: What is it I'm looking for, exactly?
\f3\fs24 \
