\f2\fs20 \cf0 Businesses hoping to reel in new customers with location-based social media discounts are discovering it takes more than casting a line for customers to bite.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Sending digital coupons to any consumer within a 100-foot radius doesn't necessarily lead to more sales or foot traffic, according to a University of Pittsburgh study.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The study, conducted by Pitt's School of Information Sciences and the New Jersey-based Stevens Institute of Technology concludes that location-based advertising through social media sites such as Foursquare and Facebook can reap benefits for businesses in the right neighborhoods - if they offer those deals at the right time - but many businesses have to work harder to make promotions successful.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Foursquare, which launched in 2009, has grown to more than 50 million users taking advantage of check-in services, and nearly 2 million businesses have signed on to the app to gain access to those users. Like Foursquare, the location based advertising industry itself is expected to surge from a $1.66 billion global market in 2013 to a projected $14.8 billion by 2018, according to Swedish analyst firm Berg Insight.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 An analysis of data collected from 14 million venues over seven months through Foursquare - a social media site where users "check in" to show exact locations to friends and other users - revealed a 50-50 split between the number of businesses that saw an increase in check-ins during the time deals were offered and those that saw no increase.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Further study showed the three most important elements to the successful deals campaigns were the particular venue's existing popularity (based on total Foursquare check-ins), the details of the deals being offered, and the population density surrounding the business.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 In other words, a popular Forbes Avenue eatery sending out a back-to-school deal during Pitt's freshman rush will likely see more check-ins than a lesser-known business across town offering a similar discount.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Even if a business falls short in each category, it's no reason to abandon location-based deals altogether.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "We are not saying that special deals are not useful to business owners, quite the contrary," said Konstantinos Pelechrinis, lead researcher and assistant professor at Pitt's School of Information Sciences in a news release. "What we are saying is that business owners should be well-versed on the best means for using social media and they should have realistic expectations on how social media can help their individual ventures grow."
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Mr. Pelechrinis said small business owners in less populated areas should make efforts to combine location-based deals with promotions made offline to raise awareness of the campaign and the store itself. He added that companies should take advantage of location-based social media advertising that pushes notifications to smartphones to alert customers when they're approaching businesses offering deals.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Lucas Evans, founder of East Liberty-based location technology marketing company Nectr, said his company takes a hyper-targeted approach by sending customized notifications to customers who opt-in to the service only when they are actually inside the store offering the deal.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 He said the old model of sending coupons to anyone with a smartphone and an active app dilutes the relevance of the message.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "Just having a deal to 'check-in' and receive a free side of fries is not going to resonate or be a significant factor in driving today's on-the-go consumer to your restaurant," Mr. Evans said. "But if I am on Google and searching for places to eat near me and I see the same offer for a restaurant that is in my immediate vicinity, then I am much more likely to take advantage of it.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 "So it's important to take into consideration the consumers' state of mind, meaning when, where and how your content is being delivered," he said.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 Mr. Pelechrinis, who is also head of Pitt's Network 
\f0\i\b \ul Data Science
\f2\i0\b0 \ulnone  Lab, said the study results are part of an ongoing effort to examine issues impacting small businesses and the local economy. In coming months, he and his team will examine how street festivals and fairs impact local small businesses and how road closures due to construction affect sales.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 The study was presented at the International Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence Conference on Web and Social Media in Oxford, England. Pitt doctoral candidate Ke Zhang and Theodoros Lappas, assistant professor in the Stevens Institute of Technology's School of Business, were coauthors.
