\f2\fs20 \cf0 You know we've entered a new era in the region's economy when the fastest growing companies have names like APAR, RAPIDIGM, intelitran and Greyfox.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 They don't exactly roll off the tongue or carry the same heft as U.S. Steel, Westinghouse or even Alcoa, do they? Well, get used to it.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 As Pittsburgh plays catch-up with the rest of the country, it's these smaller, young technology-oriented companies that are going to be doing a lot of the growing and hiring and leading these days.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 That's not to downplay the role and importance of our big institutions, but the truth is, for many old-timers, the primary focus in recent years has been on survival. Some haven't made it, and others are significantly leaner. So it is that the region, as much from necessity as desire, must look elsewhere for job growth.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 To encourage the companies making it happen, the Pittsburgh Technology Council for the past three years has scoured southwestern Pennsylvania for hidden technology stars. Last night, the trade organization feted its latest batch, the Pittsburgh Technology 50 - the 50 fastest-growing high tech concerns, based on 1998 sales growth.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 It just so happens that the Pittsburgh Technology 50 came out the same day that Inc. magazine unveiled its list of the nation's 500 fastest-growing private companies. The region was well represented by eight companies, led by Efficient Machine Tool Sales, a 5-year-old producer and distributor of equipment in Bridgeville that was a lucky 13th on the Inc. 500 list (see below).
