\f2\fs20 \cf0 At a time when even the words "start-ups" and "new technology" cause investors to sweat, it's worth noting that many of this year's winners in the Pittsburgh Technology Council's annual look at the region's 50 leading high-tech firms are wizened veterans of the business world.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  There was North Huntingdon-based Extrude Hone Corp., which makes equipment to improve machining and finishing manufacturing and has been around since 1966.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  There was Medrad Inc., the Indianola maker of medical imaging equipment that's even older -- it was founded in 1964.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  But Extrude Hone and Medrad are whippersnappers compared with LLI Technologies Inc., the great-grandfather of the bunch. Founded in 1910 when it was known as Hunting-Davis Co., the Downtown-based provider of engineering design and technical services ranked among the top 10 local companies that provide services that help high-tech firms survive and grow.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 In fact, among the Hawaiian-shirted crowd of 500 who gathered last night at Carnegie Music Hall in a "Hawaii Five-O" theme, were several relative geezers.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  Nine were founded before 1980, when the words "high tech" hadn't fully entered the American lexicon, and 20 were more than 10 years old -- ancient to many techies.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  The comparatively high number of "old" high-tech stars wasn't entirely surprising. That's because the council, along with accounting firm PriceWaterhouseCoopers, changed the criteria for choosing winners in a way that better reflected the works of those that have been steady performers over the years -- not just flashes in the pan.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  Unlike past years, when revenue growth was the main criteria, it and related financial measures only accounted for a fifth of the score this year. Innovation, corporate citizenship, job growth and retention and customer satisfaction received equal attention.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  "We're confident we've adopted a best-practices standard," said council spokesman Kevin Lane.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  To be sure, youthful stars still represented the majority of this year's winners, the youngest being Corporate Solutions and Fidelity Flight Simulation Inc., both of which were founded last year and employ six and five, respectively.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  They were among the 10 so-called Rising Stars, companies incorporated in the last three years that exhibit potential and offer unique and promising products and services.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  As for the chief executive officer of the year, James Cashman III is an industry veteran even though he's only been at the helm of Ansys Inc., the 22-year-old Canonsburg-based supplier of analytical and engineering software for product design, since early 2000.
\f3\fs24 \

\f2\fs20  Cashman has worked at Ansys and other technology companies for 26 years.
